    {
      "id": "19655b1490a890234a91bbf482c7a9034e2c5141",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-11 22:30:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nIn addition to the comment I wonder if we should make cl_cache interface to be an OSC thing?\n\nBasiclly we'll have something like cl_cache_init that you'd call from llite (and it would take care of initial alloc and init, and return the pointer) and then\ncl_cache_decref (or the like) that would be called every time a reference is dropped (As opposed to current immediate decref with inline FREE if refcount is 0). That would also need to have a \"cl_cache_addref() also to be called every time a reference is taken.\n\nFinally in the free case the atomic_dec_and_test() && FREE() code is fundamentally racy (because nothing prevents another user from appearing and doing addref after we did the check) - so this needs an extra explanation of why in our code this is impossible (e.g. because all OSCs are instantiated and no new ones could appear when we are able to do shutdown (but then again - what if somebody is adding a new OST into the system as the a client is unmounting?)) or a proper handling of this race really needs to happen.\n\nLastly, please create this patch against master first for further iterations and we'll backport it to older versions as needed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
